com.software.reuze

Class al_CurrentBest

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.software.reuze.al_CurrentBest
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    al_i_Learner

    public class al_CurrentBest
extends Object
implements al_i_Learner
    Implements the CURRENT-BEST-LEARNING algorithm from page 771, AIMAv3. The algorithm works by creating hypotheses (in essence, first order logic sentences) that are compared with examples (also sentences). In this class, we use Hypothesis to represent the FOL hypotheses and FOLExample to convert the common Example class to FOL.
    Author:
    Ciaran O'Reilly, Andrew Brown

    • Method Detail

      • currentBestLearning

        public mf_Hypothesis currentBestLearning(al_Examples examples,
                                mf_Hypothesis h)
        Artificial Intelligence A Modern Approach (3rd Edition): Figure 19.2, page 771.

         function CURRENT-BEST-LEARNING(examples, h) returns a hypothesis or fail

   if examples is empty then
      return h
   e <- FIRST(examples)
   if e is consistent with h then
      return CURRENT-BEST-LEARNING(REST(examples), h)
   else if e is a false positive for h then
     for each h' in specializations of h consistent with examples seen so far do
       h'' <- CURRENT-BEST-LEARNING(REST(examples), h')
       if h'' != fail then return h''
   else if e is a false negative for h then
     for each h' in generalization of h consistent with examples seen so far do
       h'' <- CURRENT-BEST-LEARNING(REST(examples), h')
       if h'' != fail then return h''
   return fail
        Figure 19.2 The current-best-hypothesis learning algorithm. It searches for a consistent hypothesis that fits all the examples and backtracks when no consistent specialization/generalization can be found. To start the algorithm, any hypothesis can be passed in; it will be specialized or generalized as needed.
